facts.title: The Earths rotation is gradually slowing
facts.fact: This deceleration is happening almost imperceptibly, at approximately 17 milliseconds per hundred years, although the rate at which it occurs is not perfectly uniform. This has the effect of lengthening our days, but it happens so slowly that it could be as much as 140 million years before the length of a day will have increased to 25 hours.

facts.title: The Earth was once believed to be the centre of the universe
facts.fact: Due to the apparent movements of the Sun and planets in relation to their viewpoint, ancient scientists insisted that the Earth remained static, whilst other celestial bodies travelled in circular orbits around it. Eventually, the view that the Sun was at the centre of the universe was postulated by Copernicus, though this is also not the case.

facts.title: Earth has a powerful magnetic field
facts.fact: This phenomenon is caused by the nickel-iron core of the planet, coupled with its rapid rotation. This field protects the Earth from the effects of solar wind.

facts.title: There is only one natural satellite of the planet Earth
facts.fact: As a percentage of the size of the body it orbits, the Moon is the largest satellite of any planet in our solar system. In real terms, however, it is only the fifth largest natural satellite.

facts.title: Earth is the only planet not named after a god
facts.fact: The other seven planets in our solar system are all named after Roman gods or goddesses. Although only Mercury, Venus, Mars, Jupiter and Saturn were named during ancient times, because they were visible to the naked eye, the Roman method of naming planets was retained after the discovery of Uranus and Neptune.

facts.title: The Earth is the densest planet in the Solar System
facts.fact: This varies according to the part of the planet; for example, the metallic core is denser than the crust. The average density of the Earth is approximately 5.52 grams per cubic centimetre.

facts.title: Mars and Earth have approximately the same landmass
facts.fact: Even though Mars has only 15% of the Earths volume and just over 10% of the Earths mass, around two thirds of the Earths surface is covered in water. Martian surface gravity is only 37% of the Earths (meaning you could leap nearly three times higher on Mars).

facts.title: Mars is home to the tallest mountain in the solar system
facts.fact: Olympus Mons, a shield volcano, is 21km high and 600km in diameter. Despite having formed over billions of years, evidence from volcanic lava flows is so recent many scientists believe it could still be active.

facts.title: Only 18 missions to Mars have been successful
facts.fact: As of September 2014 there have been 40 missions to Mars, including orbiters, landers and rovers but not counting flybys. The most recent arrivals include the Mars Curiosity mission in 2012, the MAVEN mission, which arrived on September 22, 2014, followed by the Indian Space Research Organizations MOM Mangalyaan orbiter, which arrived on September 24, 2014. The next missions to arrive will be the European Space Agencys ExoMars mission, comprising an orbiter, lander, and a rover, followed by NASAs InSight robotic lander mission, slated for launch in March 2016 and a planned arrival in September, 2016.

facts.title: Mars has the largest dust storms in the solar system
facts.fact: They can last for months and cover the entire planet. The seasons are extreme because its elliptical (oval-shaped) orbital path around the Sun is more elongated than most other planets in the solar system.

facts.title: On Mars the Sun appears about half the size as it does on Earth
facts.fact: At the closest point to the Sun, the Martian southern hemisphere leans towards the Sun, causing a short, intensely hot summer, while the northern hemisphere endures a brief, cold winter: at its farthest point from the Sun, the Martian northern hemisphere leans towards the Sun, causing a long, mild summer, while the southern hemisphere endures a lengthy, cold winter.

facts.title: Pieces of Mars have fallen to Earth
facts.fact: Scientists have found tiny traces of Martian atmosphere within meteorites violently ejected from Mars, then orbiting the solar system amongst galactic debris for millions of years, before crash landing on Earth. This allowed scientists to begin studying Mars prior to launching space missions.

facts.title: A year on Mercury is just 88 days long
facts.fact: One solar day (the time from noon tonoon on the planets surface) on Mercury lasts the equivalent of 176 Earth dayswhile the sidereal day (the time for 1 rotation in relation to a fixed point) lasts59 Earth days. Mercury is nearly tidally locked to the Sun and over time this has slowed the rotation of the planet to almost match its orbit around the Sun. Mercury also has the highest orbital eccentricity of all the planets with its distance from the Sun ranging from 46 to 70 million km.

facts.title: Mercury is the smallest planet in the Solar System
facts.fact: One of five planets visible with the naked eye a, Mercury is just 4,879 Kilometres across its equator, compared with 12,742 Kilometres for the Earth.

facts.title: Mercury is the second densest planet
facts.fact: Even though the planet is small, Mercury is very dense. Each cubic centimetre has a density of 5.4 grams, with only the Earth having a higher density. This is largely due to Mercury being composed mainly of heavy metals and rock.

facts.title: Mercury has wrinkles
facts.fact: As the iron core of the planet cooled and contracted, the surface of the planet became wrinkled. Scientist have named these wrinkles, Lobate Scarps. These Scarps can be up to a mile high and hundreds of miles long.

facts.title: Mercury has a molten core
facts.fact: In recent years scientists from NASA have come to believe the solid iron core of Mercury could in fact be molten. Normally the core of smaller planets cools rapidly, but after extensive research, the results were not in line with those expected from a solid core. Scientists now believe the core to contain a lighter element such as sulphur, which would lower the melting temperature of the core material. It is estimated Mercurys core makes up 42% of its volume, while the Earths core makes up 17%.

facts.title: Mercury is only the second hottest planet
facts.fact: Despite being further from the Sun,Venusexperiences higher temperatures.The surface of Mercury which faces the Sun sees temperatures of up to 427C, whilst on the alternate side this can be as low as -173C. This is due to the planet having no atmosphere to help regulate the temperature.

facts.title: A day on Venus lasts longer than a year
facts.fact: It takes 243 Earth days to rotate once on its axis (sidereal day). The planets orbit around the Sun takes 225 Earth days, compared to the Earths 365. A day on the surface of Venus (solar day) takes 117 Earth days.

facts.title: Venus rotates in the opposite direction to most other planets
facts.fact: This means that Venus is rotating in the opposite direction to the Sun, this is also known as a retrograde rotation. One possible reason for this might be a collision with an asteroid or other object.

facts.title: Venus is the second brightest object in the night sky
facts.fact: Only the Moon is brighter. With a magnitude of between -3.8 to -4.6 Venus is so bright it can be seen during daytime on a clear day.

facts.title: Atmospheric pressure on Venus is 92 times greater than the Earths
facts.fact: Due to this crushing small asteroids when they enter its atmosphere Venus has not small craters. The pressure felt on Venus surface is equivalent to that deep beneath the sea on Earth.

facts.title: Venus is often called the Earths sister planet
facts.fact: The Earth and Venus are very similar in size with only a 638 km difference in diameter and Venus having 81.5% of the Earths mass. Both also have a central core, a molten mantle and a crust.

facts.title: The same side of Venus always faces the Earth when at their closest
facts.fact: It is possible this is due to the Earths gravational influence.

facts.title: Jupiter is the fourth brightest object in the solar system
facts.fact: Only the Sun, Moon and Venus are brighter. It is one of five planets visible to the naked eye from Earth.

facts.title: The ancient Babylonians were the first to record their sightings of Jupiter
facts.fact: This was around the 7th or 8th century BC. Jupiter is named after the king of the Roman gods. To the Greeks, it represented Zeus, the god of thunder. The Mesopotamians saw Jupiter as the god Marduk and patron of the city of Babylon. Germanic tribes saw this planet as Donar, or Thor.

facts.title: Jupiter has the shortest day of all the planets
facts.fact: It turns on its axis once every 9 hours and 55 minutes. The rapid rotation flattens the planet slightly, giving it an oblate shape.

facts.title: Jupiter orbits the Sun once every 11.8 Earth years
facts.fact: From our point of view on Earth, it appears to move slowly in the sky, taking months to move from one constellation to another.

facts.title: Jupiter has unique cloud features
facts.fact: The upper atmosphere of Jupiter is divided into cloud belts and zones. They are made primarily of ammonia crystals, sulfur, and mixtures of the two compounds.

facts.title: The Great Red Spot is a huge storm on Jupiter
facts.fact: It has raged for at least 350 years. It is so large that three Earths could fit inside it.

facts.title: Saturn is the most distant planet that can be seen with the naked eye
facts.fact: It is the fifth brightest object in the solar system and is also easily studied through binoculars or a small telescope.

facts.title: Saturn was known to the ancients, including the Babylonians and Far Eastern observers
facts.fact: It is named for the Roman god Saturnus, and was known to the Greeks as Cronus.

facts.title: Saturn is the flattest planet
facts.fact: Its polar diameter is 90% of its equatorial diameter, this is due to its low density and fast rotation. Saturn turns on its axis once every 10 hours and 34 minutes giving it the second-shortest day of any of the solar systems planets.

facts.title: Saturn orbits the Sun once every 29.4 Earth years
facts.fact: Its slow movement against the backdrop of stars earned it the nickname of 'Lubadsagush' from the ancient Assyrians. The name means 'oldest of the old'.

facts.title: Saturns upper atmosphere is divided into bands of clouds
facts.fact: The top layers are mostly ammonia ice. Below them, the clouds are largely water ice. Below are layers of cold hydrogen and sulfur ice mixtures.

facts.title: Saturn has oval-shaped storms similar to Jupiter's
facts.fact: The region around its north pole has a hexagonal-shaped pattern of clouds. Scientists think this may be a wave pattern in the upper clouds. The planet also has a vortex over its south pole that resembles a hurricane-like storm.
